        "topic": "Degrees of Certainty in the Past Tense",
        "explanation": "Use the simple past-tense form when you are 100 percent certain. *Terrence was home last night.* (I called him and talked to him.) *Dennis ate a big salad for lunch.* (I saw him eat it.) Use *must have* + participle when you are almost certain. *Karen must have been hungry.* (She ate three eggs for breakfast.) *You must have had a good time.* (You look happy.) When you are less than 50 percent certain, use *may have* + participle, *might have* + participle or *could have* + participle. *Ken may have been at work yesterday.* (He wasn't at home, but it's possible he was somewhere else.) *June might have taken the bus to work.* (She didn't take her car, but maybe she walked.) To express negative certainty in the past, use the simple past negative form of the verb. *Tom wasn't at the meeting yesterday.* *Bridget didn't go to school yesterday.* When you are very certain, use *couldn't have* + participle or *can't have* + participle. *Carmen couldn't have gotten lost.* (She has a good sense of direction.) *Greta can't have forgotten our lunch date again!* (We've been friends for too long.) When you are a little less certain, use *must not have* + participle. *Beth must not have heard us knocking.* (She was playing music loudly.) When you are less than 50 percent certain, use *may not have* + participle or *might not have* + participle. *Erin may not have arrived yet.* (Her train may be running late.) ",
