        "explanation": "There are two forms of the real conditional in English. The present real conditional describes actions that are repeated or habitual, and the verb in the *if* clause is in the present tense. *If I work too much, I get tired.* *If I take the bus to school, I get there in about thirty minutes.* The future real conditional describes a future relationship. Notice that the verb in the *if* clause is in the present tense. *If I cut back on fats and carbohydrates, I will lose weight.* *If I make cookies, the neighborhood children will come over.* *The dog will bark if you make a lot of noise.* ",
