        "explanation": "If the real conditional expresses real actions, then the unreal conditional expresses actions that are untrue, hypothetical, or contrary to fact. Notice that the *if* clause takes a past-tense verb, and the result clause takes a verb with *would*. *If I had the appetite, I would order the all-you-can-eat special.* *If I had the time, I would make you a birthday cake.* *Susan would quit her job if she had another one.* When using the verb *to be*, it's important to remember to use the form *were* in the *if* clause for both singular and plural. *If I were you, I would go to the movies with Jim.* *If that food were more nutritious, I'd eat it too.* ",
